rectResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EDuring the early follicular phase, follicle stimulating hormone (FSH) levels stimulate \u003Cstrong\u003Efollicular recruitment\u003C/strong\u003E. Multiple primordial follicles begin developing into primary and secondary follicles.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis phase happens prior to \u003Cstrong\u003Eovulation\u003C/strong\u003E, which occurs mid-cycle in response to the luteinizing hormone surge. \u003Cstrong\u003ELuteinization\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Ecorpus luteum formation\u003C/strong\u003E occur after ovulation during the luteal phase. \u003Cstrong\u003EPeak estradiol production\u003C/strong\u003E occurs in the late follicular phase, just before ovulation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMost recruited follicles will undergo atresia, with typically only one becoming the dominant follicle that will eventually ovulate.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The early follicular phase is characterized by rising follicle stimulating hormone levels leading to follicular recruitment and development","Multiple follicles begin development but most undergo atresia, with typically only one becoming dominant","Luteinization and ovulation occur during the late follicular/ovulatory phase, not the early follicular phase"],"references":["Evans, T. J., \u0026 Ganjam, V. K. (2017). Reproductive anatomy and physiology. In Reproductive and Developmental Toxicology (pp. 7-37). Academic Press","Melmed, S., Polonsky, K. S., Larsen, P. R., \u0026 Kronenberg, H. M. (2015). Williams textbook of endocrinology E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Clark, O. H., Duh, Q. Y., Kebebew, E., Gosnell, J. E., \u0026 Shen, W. T. (Eds.). (2016). Textbook of endocrine surgery. JP Medical Ltd","Young, W. F. (2011). Netter\u0027s Endocrine System: Netter Collection of Medical Illustrations: Endocrine System E-book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Wass, J. A., \u0026 Stewart, P. M. (Eds.). (2011). Oxford textbook of endocrinology and diabetes. Oxford University Press, USA"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56646"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15689"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56646","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/56646"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-17T19:25:26+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-17T19:25:51+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8380"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71173"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4935","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4935"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd5a","name":"Reproductive System (Female)","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:16:52+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-21T12:54:35+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGro